    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-01-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-01-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="270"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d270">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.51/3801</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lindsay</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 7</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-01-10">10 January,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With further reference to your Note No.
                    862.51/3782 of December 29th regarding the treatment of foreign loans by the
                    German Government I have the honour, under instructions from His Majesty’s <pb
                        facs="0434" n="334" xml:id="pg_334"/> Principal Secretary of State for
                    Foreign Affairs, to inform you that His Majesty’s Government in the United
                    Kingdom have noted with satisfaction the attitude of the United States
                    Government on this question.</p>
                <p>Instructions have been sent to His Majesty’s Ambassador in Berlin to keep in
                    touch with his United States colleague on this matter: to show him the text of
                    the latest note addressed by His Majesty’s Government to the German Government:
                    and to ask in return to be informed of the terms of the corresponding United
                    States note. The Financial Adviser to His Majesty’s Embassy at Berlin has been
                    authorised to discuss, if necessary, technical details with his United States
                    colleague.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>R. C. <hi rend="smallcaps">Lindsay</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
